        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 23,
            "text": "Enteroviruses are common human pathogens ,",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "and infections are particularly frequent in children . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "Severe infections can lead to a variety of diseases ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 3,
            "text": "including poliomyelitis , aseptic meningitis , myocarditis and neonatal sepsis . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 3,
            "text": "Enterovirus infections have also been implicated in asthmatic exacerbations and type 1 diabetes . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 3,
            "text": "The large disease spectrum of the closely related enteroviruses may be partially , but not fully , explained by differences in tissue tropism . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "The molecular mechanisms",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "by which enteroviruses cause disease",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "are poorly understood ,",
            "relation": "SAME-UNIT"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 9,
            "text": "but there is increasing evidence",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "that the two enteroviral proteases , 2A pro and 3C pro , are important mediators of pathology . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "These proteases perform the posttranslational proteolytic processing of the viral polyprotein ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 12,
            "text": "but they also cleave several host - cell proteins",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "in order to promote the production of new virus particles ,",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 14,
            "text": "as well as to evade the cellular antiviral immune responses . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 12,
            "text": "Enterovirus - associated processing of cellular proteins may also contribute to pathology ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "parent": 16,
            "text": "as elegantly demonstrated by the 2A pro -mediated cleavage of dystrophin in cardiomyocytes",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "parent": 17,
            "text": "contributing to Coxsackievirus - induced cardiomyopathy . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "It is likely that improved tools",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 20,
            "parent": 19,
            "text": "to identify targets for these proteases",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 21,
            "parent": 19,
            "text": "will reveal additional host protein substrates",
            "relation": "SAME-UNIT"
        },
        {
            "id": 22,
            "parent": 21,
            "text": "that can be linked to specific enterovirus - associated diseases . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 23,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "Here , we discuss the function of the enteroviral proteases in the virus replication cycle",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 24,
            "parent": 23,
            "text": "and review the current knowledge",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 25,
            "parent": 24,
            "text": "regarding how these proteases modulate the infected cell",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 26,
            "parent": 25,
            "text": "in order to favour virus replication ,",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 27,
            "parent": 25,
            "text": "including ways",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 28,
            "parent": 27,
            "text": "to avoid detection by the immune system . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 29,
            "parent": 23,
            "text": "We also highlight new possibilities for the identification of protease - specific cellular targets and thereby a way",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 30,
            "parent": 29,
            "text": "to discover novel mechanisms",
            "relation": "ENABLEMENT"
        },
        {
            "id": 31,
            "parent": 30,
            "text": "contributing to disease . <S> <P>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        }
    ]
